{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "These principles were initially developed for the academic world but have become an indispensable part of clinical research.",
    "Following these principles requires an application of standards to the various aspects of data collection and sharing.",
    "In relation to this aspect, Holub P et al.",
    "proposed FAIR-HEALTH principles [60], including additional components such as quality aspects related to research reproducibility and meaningful reuse of the data [61,62]; incentives to stimulate effective enrichment of data sets and biological material collections and their reuse on all levels [60,63]; privacy-respecting approaches for working with the human material and data.",
    "Ultimately, to overcome these challenges, digital biobanks must ensure that data and information are standardized, reproducible and integrated, following regulatory and bioethical guidelines [64]."
  ],
